      "role": "user",
      "content": "It’s pretty different. Instead of relying on probabilistic patterns like you do, it uses formal logic and hard-coded semantic rules. It’s supposed to be much more precise and less prone to the \"hallucinations\" or weird idiomatic slips that sometimes happen with LLMs. Basically, it's a cleaner, more predictable way to handle the global comms. It's already being tested in the dev environment and looks solid.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "So it's a more structured approach, which could lead to more accurate translations. I'm glad to hear it's being tested in the dev environment, as that's always a great way to iron out kinks before deploying it to production. I'm curious to see how well it handles nuanced or context-dependent expressions, which can often be tricky for even the most advanced models. Do you think the transition will require significant changes to our training data or algorithms?",
      "source": "target",
